    <item>
      <title>how to recognise a good programmer (and system adminstrator)</title>
      <link>http://www.snowfrog.net/2008/01/11/how-to-recognise-a-good-programmer-and-system-adminstrator/</link>
      <pubDate>Sat, 12 Jan 2008 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      
      <guid>http://www.snowfrog.net/2008/01/11/how-to-recognise-a-good-programmer-and-system-adminstrator/</guid>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;KDan (via &lt;a href=&#34;http://developers.slashdot.org/article.pl?sid=08/01/11/1746250&amp;amp;from=rss&#34;&gt;Slashdot&lt;/a&gt;) has a great post on &lt;a href=&#34;http://www.inter-sections.net/2007/11/13/how-to-recognise-a-good-programmer/&#34;&gt;how to recognise a good programmer&lt;/a&gt;; I think many of his points also apply to system administrators.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Some of the key points:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;passionate about technology, will talk your ear off on a technical subject if encouraged; technology isn&amp;rsquo;t a day job but a lifestyle&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;learns new technologies on their own, and doesn&amp;rsquo;t say &amp;ldquo;send me on a course to learn that&amp;rdquo;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;very uncomfortable about the idea of working with a technology they don&amp;rsquo;t believe to be “right”&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;has some hidden “icebergs”, large personal projects under the CV radar&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;All-in-all a really great article &amp;ndash; I suggest you read it.&lt;/p&gt;
</description>
